03783nam a22004695i 9780226771496DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267714967 a10.7208/97802267714962doi  a(DE-B1597)523878  a(OCoLC)754216103  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aStaub, Michael E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMadness Is Civilization :bWhen the Diagnosis Was Social, 1948-1980 /cMichael E. Staub. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: When the Diagnosis Was Social -- t1. Society as the Patient -- t2. Enough to Drive Anybody Crazy -- t3. Suffering from Contingencies -- t4. The Therapeutic State -- tPart II: The Revolution in Feeling -- t5. The Insanity Trip -- t6. Person Envy -- t7. A Fashionable Kind of Slander -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1960s and 1970s, a popular diagnosis for America’s problems was that society was becoming a madhouse. In this intellectual and cultural history, Michael E. Staub examines a time when many believed insanity was a sane reaction to obscene social conditions, psychiatrists were agents of repression, asylums were gulags for society’s undesirables, and mental illness was a concept with no medical basis. Madness Is Civilization explores the general consensus that societal ills—from dysfunctional marriage and family dynamics to the Vietnam War, racism, and sexism—were at the root of mental illness. Staub chronicles the surge in influence of socially attuned psychodynamic theories along with the rise of radical therapy and psychiatric survivors' movements. He shows how the theories of antipsychiatry held unprecedented sway over an enormous range of medical, social, and political debates until a bruising backlash against these theories—part of the reaction to the perceived excesses and self-absorptions of the 1960s—effectively distorted them into caricatures. Throughout, Staub reveals that at stake in these debates of psychiatry and politics was nothing less than how to think about the institution of the family, the nature of the self, and the prospects for, and limits of, social change. The first study to describe how social diagnostic thinking emerged, Madness Is Civilization casts new light on the politics of the postwar era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMental illnesszUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226771496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226771496.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles